    {
      "block_id": "3394750c-f3ba-8021-ad02-f5744ff3a8e6",
      "heading": "Abstract",
      "rows": [
        [
          "Task",
          "Context",
          "Teaching Method",
          "Student Performance Definition",
          "Target",
          "Students",
          "Courses",
          "Data sources",
          "Features",
          "Moment of Prediction",
          "Preprocessing Details",
          "Models",
          "Assessment Strategy",
          "Performance Metric: Best Model",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "Higher Education",
          "Flipped Classroom",
          "Final Mark in a Course",
          "High achievers (A- to A+), Moderate performers (B- to B+), At-risk students (C+ or lower)",
          "Course 1: 183 students; Course 2: 60 students",
          "2 introductory statistics courses at 2 public research universities in California",
          "CourseKata online textbook trace data, embedded formative assessments, chapter summaries, final letter grades",
          "[Reading-related: sess_count, sess_avg_dur, sess_max_dur, pages_per_sess, read_time_total, engage_ratio; Formative-assessment-related: quiz_score, first_attempt_acc, final_attempt_acc, avg_attempts, summary_word_count]",
          "Chapter-level early prediction throughout the course; models evaluated after each completed chapter",
          "Authors engineered 11 chapter-level features for each of 12 chapters (132 total features). Reading traces were segmented into sessions using a 10-minute inactivity threshold; sessions under 1 minute and sessions from end-of-chapter quizzes were removed from reading-feature construction. Data were standardized with z-score normalization using training-set scalers only. 5-fold stratified cross-validation, repeated 5 times, was used. Training data were balanced with SMOTE. For early prediction, the authors created an augmented dataset containing all prefixes of each student’s chapter sequence, masking later chapters as missing.\n\n\n\n",
          "Random Forest (RF), sequence model based on RNN/GRU, chapter ensemble of RF classifiers",
          "Within Course 1: 5-fold cross-validation repeated 5 times. Cross-institution generalization: train on Course 1, test on Course 2. Models compared across chapter-by-chapter early prediction.",
          "Within Course 1:\n\n{AUC: 0.86 - Sequence Model by Chapters 10-12}\n\nCross-Institution:\n\n{AUC: 0.81 - Sequence Model by Chapters 10-12}",
          "Main contribution is showing that a system designed for modelability can support predictive models that generalize across institutions. The strongest model was the sequence model with augmented data, especially in the cross-institution test. The study is also interesting because it uses behavioral-only textbook interaction metrics, not demographic or prior-grade predictors, and still achieves strong early prediction.",
          "Only 2 institutions and both were public research universities in California, so broader generalizability still needs testing. Sample size is modest, especially for Course 2. The target is an ordinal 3-class grouping based on letter grades rather than raw score prediction. Features come from a shared CourseKata environment, so transferability may depend on similarly instrumented platforms."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 3
    }
  ],
